The Prague Stock Exchange finished with fewer points at the end of the day
After the rapid fall of the morning, the Prague Stock Exchange corrected its losses.
<0xC4><0x8C>EZ stock transactions reached about half the value they have on a normal day.
The Prague Stock Exchange, at the beginning of trading Tuesday, reacted immediately to Monday’s fall when it fell to about 6%.
The decline this time is due to the fall in Wall Street stocks.
Also here is the market reaction to the result of the vote of the American Assembly of Representatives that refused to support the stabilization plan of the secretary of the financial sector.
Fall in stocks in Asia
Asian stocks suffered a dramatic fall on Tuesday, though the index eventually softened some of the losses throughout the day.
The Hong Kong Hang Seng Stock Exchange’s index throughout its financial day marked almost four percent, although it later mitigated its losses by reducing the decline by nearly 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises index, which tracks the movements of Chinese stocks on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange, fell 3.8 percent, while markets in Shanghai were closed.
The shares of the Sydney Stock Exchange lost more than five percent but, in the end, the losses fell to 4.3 percent.
The Taiwan Stock Exchange, according to the index secretary, fell to 3.6 percent.
“The planned rescue actions in the U.S. are unsafe and this influences the financial market around the world,” said Hong Kong Currency Bureau Chief Joseph Yam.
Although Hong Kong is a part of China, it alone determines its monetary policy, i.e. without dependence on the Central Bank of China.
Hong Kong’s interest rates are at the same level as those of the United States.
U.S. lawmakers should get back together as soon as possible, according to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, and pass a proposal to support the financial system.
Otherwise, it threatens that the falls will be felt in other countries.
Bloody bath of American stocks
On Monday, the American Assembly of Representatives rejected the financial system aid plan to which $700 billion (nearly 12 trillion kroner) should be dedicated.
Lawmakers, in that way, ignored President George Bush’s invitation to support his plan.
For Bush, the plan would address the root causes of the financial crisis and help stabilize the entire economy.
On Monday, U.S. stocks experienced a bloody plunge and mainly the stock index picked up the biggest drop in more than 20 years.
The Dow Jones index fell to nearly seven percent, a similar drop in volume last recorded in 1987.
The index fell already before it was announced but as soon as it was shown that the proposal of the assembly did not go ahead, the index began to fall freely.
Congress Withdraws: U.S. Government May Inject $700 Billion Into Banking
The highest representatives of Congress and government, President George W. Bush, agreed to a pact on broad terms of financial aid to the American financial system.
The vote will take place early next week.
U.S. lawmakers sparked a gap in talks on approving the bailout plan in its form to help the U.S. financial system with the amount of $700 billion (approximately 12 trillion kroner).
However, it is not yet won.
Congressmen must fine-tune some details of the contract before they can make public the final form of the law and have it voted on.
The plan to help the financial system will be discussed Monday in the House of Representatives.
Barney Frank, chairman of the Financial Services and Assembly Banking Committee, told Reuters on Sunday.
According to some sources, the vote on the plan could be held in the Senate not earlier than Wednesday.
According to economists, the arrival of the ratification of the bailout plan should represent the announcement of a first psychologically significant factor for the revitalization of the financial market.
Then, however, there will be "disenchantment" thanks to the complex mechanisms whose aid to the market will also reach in practice.
Paulson: The plan must be effective
“We have made a great advance.
We have resolved our dissenting views on how the package of measures for market stabilization should take shape," Democrat Nancy Pelosia told Bloomberg.
According to her, the final vote could still be held on Sunday.
Representatives of lawmakers met Sunday night with Finance Minister Henry Paulson to give a definitive form to the Government Fund.
It should buy unsold mortgage assets from financial companies that lead financial companies to heavy losses and threaten the stability of the entire system.
“We are about to close the agreement on the plan, which will work and should also be effective in the market.
We still need to continue with the sanitation plan, but I think we’re already on it,” Paulson said.
A Sign for Asian Businesses
The global financial crisis has a strong impact on the rapidly declining stock market.
According to Nevada Democratic Sen. Harry Reid, lawmakers are doing everything they can to get Congress to definitively approve a deal on Sunday.
They want to reassure investors about the Asian financial market as these are the ones in the first time zone and where Congress could influence Monday’s trade.
However, for now there is nothing clear with certainty about when the two chambers of the American Congress will vote and, not even, if they will not stagnate at the last moment with some problem.
Lawmakers believe it will be approved in the coming days.
The law, however, will undergo a number of changes.
The total amount intended to help the system should be divided into two parts.
The first $350 billion must be made available as soon as possible, as President George Bush called for.
However, Congress can block the release of the remaining amount if it has the impression that the program does not fulfill its function, which would be another $100 billion and, later, the last $350 billion.
Bush praised the progress of the meetings
On the other hand, the president can veto this decision but Congress can overcome its veto by a majority vote.
Despite these changes, the basic idea of the program was to earn financial resources for the repurchase of bad mortgage bonds whose value fell because hundreds of thousands of Americans are unable to finish paying their mortgages.
“We have worked everything.
The House of Representatives would have to be prepared to vote on the bill on Sunday, and the Senate on Monday," Republican Senator Judd Gregg said.
US President Bush is also pleased with the progress of the meetings.
His spokesman, Tony Fratto, announced that Bush is pleased with Saturday's move and that he values "the commitment of both parties to stabilize our financial market and protect our economy."
Limitation of the Armored Contract
Senate Banking Committee Chairman Christopher Dodd, head of the negotiators, said lawmakers decided on the responsibility of the program’s money to protect taxpayers’ taxes from their losses, a easing shutdown of the planned finance plan.
The new law must also limit so-called armored contracts for directors of the participating companies of the program, and creates a committee that will have control of the Fund.
This would have to be managed by the Ministry of Finance.
“We’ve worked very hard on it, and we’ve made great strides toward the agreement that will work and that will be effective for the market and for all Americans,” Paulson said.
The plan also includes helping homeowners who have problems with their payments.
The government would have to agree to the new mortgage payments it buys in order to lower monthly installment charges on debtors and enable them to keep their homes.
Marek: psychological help
The proposed plan is, according to the chief economist of Patria Finance, David Marek, a good idea that will be realized but quite difficult.
"And that is why it is not known by what mechanism and at what price the problematic assets will be bought.
This will be decisive for the distribution of losses between the financial sector and the government," Marek told iHNed.cz server this week.
Whether the plan is approved now or early next week is not so relevant, Marek said.
“Much more important is that this week the congressmen agree on their support and give it their approval as soon as possible.
This important and psychological agreement to get that approval is, at the moment, the most important thing,” Marek insisted.
Armed hand fighting: the MP3 player against the mobile.
We advise you how to choose
While almost all mobile plays MP3 files, no MP3 player can make calls.
Which seems clear that it is better to buy only the phone.
Yet there are sufficient reasons for man to acquire only the reproducer.
The choice depends practically on the manner of its use and the requirement of the future owner.
It will probably be difficult for him to acquire the most modern record player to listen to Maxim Turbulenc’s latest album.
On the other hand, this type of musical products such as LP records no longer come out, and in terms of their quality there is not a single objective reason to continue buying them.
If vinyl records with art rock, jazz or blues music are crowded on your shelves, you’re probably dreaming, at least, of this type of record player.
This is the same with music that is on the way, that is, compressed, simplified music - music in MP3.
And here there are price and quality categories.
For some it may be unacceptable to spend eight thousand crowns on a player, as well as for a Pink Floyd lover who will hardly try the twenty-crown flea market helmets.
Two ends, between which there is enough space for each.
The choice is wide.
It also decides the battery life
Some of the best players get a lot more than just playing music and even what not even most mobile phones.
No device today is as universal as the phone.
Faced with the most basic functions such as telephone, sending messages, you can play music and video, record both, you have a better or worse camera and you can even navigate.
And when we consider the Smartphone and the PDAs they will also have a small computer in their pocket.
This is a small miracle since no refrigerator can make a barbecue and no television can photograph.
The universality of mobile also brings us disadvantages.
The more functions you use on your mobile phone, the earlier the display indicator will light up asking to be recharged.
And music playback is one of the biggest energy tragons.
There are few mobile phones that can play music for more than ten or twelve hours, most of them much less.
In this sense, music players (especially the simplest ones) clearly have higher performance.
Keep in mind that cheap phones will not play for more than two hours.
If in addition to this, on top, they constantly call still get, for more safety, a charger for work - this applies also to the most expensive appliances.
With the MP3 player this problem will not have it, as even the worst ones can withstand at least 9 hours of uninterrupted operation after a charge.
Another problem occurs when recording music on mobile.
Unfortunately, only a part of the devices has the universal USB connector and, in addition, not all of them can be connected directly to the computer without special software.
Of course it is possible to record music directly on the memory card but only in some drives without reduction can connect the small memory cards that are used in mobile phones.
In players, with some exception (iPod), no special software is required.
Simply fill the device with music through the USB of the computer.
Most mobile phones and players create their own order in the music library according to the name of the performer, album title, genre or also according to the user rating.
Some devices only show a directory with tree structure similar to a Windows Finder and some recognize both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with operating system).
The player tries to serve, the mobile knows more
For the choice of a particular equipment be interested in the resistance of the accumulator, the capacity of the memory, the quality and the type of sound output and, of course, the comfort of its handling.
If you listen, above all, to the music as a background and you are going to listen to it every day only for a while, as in the tram, then it is enough with any mobile that plays.
Which practically gets any mobile phone.
You should not even be interested in the format in which the mobile or the player plays the music.
The MP3 is played by everyone and almost all the music that comes to you will be in this format.
It is among the most widespread and except for him the absolute majority of the devices play music in WMA format.
The least include the AAC format (format used by the company Apple and its iPod).
The best mobile phones also make it possible, for example, to buy music online.
All you have to do is visit the relevant pages of the operator (or any other service provider) and buy a song or an album.
This service could in itself be a weighty argument to acquire a mobile for music.
Unfortunately the offer of the operators is miserable and most are limited only to the themes of fleeting success of the radios.
The prices are also not the lowest.
However, in general, it is assumed that precisely this way of selling music (whether by GSM, internet or wireless internet) in the future will dominate the music industry.
Most people always carry a mobile phone with them.
Whenever you feel like listening to something, you’ll find the phone in your pocket, while the MP3 player will be forgotten at home.
However, it still depends on whether you always carry headphones or at least handsfree.
If not, you can use an integrated player that has virtually every mobile even if it is at least an MP3 player.
Probably the biggest advantage for many of the mobiles with music will be its price.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than three thousand.
Between three and four thousand crowns you can already acquire a good walkman.
Most of you will be limited to the absence of an input for classic headphones.
The best, even when it comes to the technical part, such as phones equipped with a 3.5 mm input. for a classic headphones, cost up to fifteen thousand.
Again, the advantage of the players is nothing more than their easy service.
The simplest players - by no means necessarily the cheapest (see our selection) - are really handled by anyone.
The minimal functions, its handling similar to the previous current cassettes or also to the turntables is evident.
It does not represent a threat in the sense that by mistake we connect to the internet with the mobile and, consequently, gigantic account for data loss.
Which device to choose
Even the cheapest mobile phones (for example, the Vodafone 527) usually have a slot to change the memory card (type M2, micro SD, etc.).
Even with the purchase of a suitable card will reach the two thousand crowns.
However, be careful.
The basic models are usually equipped only with a 2 GB maximum capacity card.
Only the most expensive have a memory of 8 GB.
If you already have a mobile phone and still want to buy a cheap MP3 player, check out Cowon, Creativ, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or Iriver.
Depending on the capacity (maximum 2 GB) it is not necessary to spend more than 1,100 crowns.
If you are considered among the most demanding music lovers, take advantage of the more specialized mobile walkman (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices have separate keys for the MP3 which makes a service as comfortable as that of the same player.
The most specialized of all is Sony Ericsson, whose mobiles of the walkman line have almost identical use as that of a standalone MP3 player.
The same service and the same category in terms of price, over the four thousand crowns, but with a greater capacity of memory (up to 16 GB) and battery (usually 15 hours, with a maximum performance of up to 35 hours), the brand mentioned more arria brings them MP3 players.
The first virtual operator will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Possibly
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite developed and our operators offer virtually all services as their Western European partners.
However, here we still lack something - the virtual operator, which would force those to be cheaper.
It's probably not going to be long before it gets here.
That Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe, we have already written on mobile.cz.
The rest was also confirmed by the Czech Telecommunications Office (<0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>) which warned that the price of SMS messages in our country is one of the most expensive in the whole Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of regulation of roaming rates you will probably come to a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile operators SMS sending from abroad will be cheaper than if they send them from home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, lacking competition that really wants to fight.
This probably seems paradoxical to us, since we have three mobile networks and their high coverage is more than 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that in the Czech market there is extreme competition.
The President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (<0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>), Pavel Dvo<0xC5><0x99><0xC3><0xA1>k, has already said that there is no place in the Czech Republic for any other operator.
It is perhaps true that for a classic operator with its own network it no longer has too many possibilities (for the rest, it would be quite difficult to find some frequency).
However, there is still a possibility - the virtual operator.
Precisely the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile phone market brought a marked drop in prices, which had to be reacted to by the classic operators as well.
At the same time, even before the entry of sharks such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile into the UK market, similar voices were heard both there and here.
It was shown that there is room for this type of operators and that they can succeed.
Otherwise, it is not necessary to look for examples too far away.
In February of this year we inform you about the premiere of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
After only half a year, this operator managed to gain more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator in the neighboring country.
On the other hand, behind Mobilking is the Penta group which, besides that, in the Czech Republic is the owner of U:fon.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on many more specific target groups.
In addition, in order for them to function effectively, they need far fewer customers than a classic operator.
They do not carry relatively large costs in the construction, operation and maintenance of the network.
In the world this type of virtual operators are usually profiled with low expenses - they offer cheap calls and SMS messages which however, is often countered with the offer of tighter services.
Thus, for example, Tesco mobile in Great Britain offers SMS at least half as cheap as the competition.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a good blow to bet on a non-trivial target group.
This operator is specifically aimed at man.
“The right man chooses Mobilking – he’s the operator he likes and can be trusted with,” says David Seibert, the CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, which works this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether such a concept as Poland could catch on in our country.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> said: "The Czech market is relatively small to access by segments on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition, from the point of view of the supply of services it is relatively saturated"
In the Czech Republic there are no possibilities, say mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if in the Czech Republic there will be some virtual operator that will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, however, in the Czech Republic does not seem too hopeful.
Rather, it is about the launch of Mobilking in other countries of our region," Jana Studni<0xC4><0x8D>kov<0xC3><0xA1>, a spokesman for the financial group Penta, said in a phone conversation for mobil.cz.
Indirectly he said that current mobile operators in the Czech Republic definitely do not bow to this idea.
Rather, they try to do everything possible so that no potential competition arises.
Interest in the launch of a virtual mobile operator is already shown by the GTS Novera group that would like to take a step further to become a real competition of Telef<0xC3><0xB3>nica O2 in the field of business customers.
"We have a great interest in this, to be able to offer our customers not only fixed telephony services but also mobile telephony.
And the sooner, the better.
With this possibility we have repeatedly met with all Czech mobile operators.
With some of them we have managed to move forward in the meetings,” said the group’s spokesman, Pavel Kaidl.
Then maybe better times flash.
It seems that, for unofficial information, the first official operator would have to arrive by the end of the year.
But for now his appearance is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
“Right now we believe the situation is ideal for the emergence of a virtual operator in the Czech market.
The Czech market compared to others is a very specific market.
So far no one has addressed us with any complex and serious project in this field," Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88>, a spokesman for Telef<0xC3><0xB3>nica O2, told mobil.cz.
Of the specificity of the Czech market refer other operators.
T-mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1>, in exceptional accordance with the opinion of O2, adds: “To date we have not registered any viable commercial project that, bilaterally beneficial, can continue to develop.”
“On the T-Mobile network, it will be difficult to find a virtual operator until the end of the year.
At this moment we should already have on the table some concrete contract that it was possible to study in such a short horizon.
Vodafone focuses its attention on meeting the requirements of a 3G license.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> adds: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and this with regard to the sharing of costs and infrastructure.
We see it as the biggest contribution from the customer’s point of view.
Vodafone’s core strategy in this field lies in the partner with whom to establish a shared network for fast mobile internet.”
Responsible offices - with operators nail and meat
The progress of mobile operators can be easily understood, but the entry of another operator would mean increasing competition which would lead to a fall in prices and thus a fall in profits.
So why facilitate entry to the competition?
When operators want to get something, they are able to pull on the same rope, proof of this is the grip when U:fon emerged.
Perhaps the biggest pressure on <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> was at the time of the entry of U:fon by the T-Mobile company.
This is attested by the public information accessible on the websites of the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>.
But precisely now U:fon serves as an argument for why not accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> adds: “Moreover, not so long ago the competitive environment in the mobile market was opened up to a fourth operator.
As far as the character of the mobile telephony market in the Czech Republic is concerned, it is natural that the entry of another player into the market would mean great requirements for him and, above all, for his services."
This is why this access to mobile operators is tremendously discouraging due to the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory body.
This is not just the position of the <0xC4><0x8C>TU, which unfortunately has no competence to intervene in commercial tenders, unlike Britain and other developed countries.
This belongs purely to the Office for the Protection of Commercial Tenderings (UOHS).
However, it expressed its typical position in the face of this problem.
“The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile phone market would be possible after an agreement on the rental of the necessary infrastructure between a mobile operator and a virtual operator has been concluded.
To date, no agreement has been concluded since the offer of potential stakeholders was not interesting enough for classic operators," added Kristian Chalupa, from the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS foreign relations department, to our question.
These statements do not surprise the representatives of the operators.
For offices that must represent the interests of consumers it is more than a consideration, other than that they must note that no one takes advantage of their position in the market.
Especially when Kristi<0xC3><0xA1>n Chalupa adds: "Overseas where virtual operators operate normally we can see that their entry into the market contributed to lower prices of mobile phone services"
Clearly, the pressure on the proper functioning of the market media and the fall in prices are not in the interest of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
Really what is dramatically shocking in this whole case is the dissonant reactions that result from the three mobile operators.
The question of whether it is really a coincidence, is offered on its own.
It is the same as with the price of gasoline at the gas stations because it is clear that it is the work of chance and a hard fight for competition.
“The Office in this regard has found no signs of unfair competition and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position, therefore they do not have a corresponding increase in responsibility in their actions on the market.
The tools needed to open up the mobile market to virtual operators, rather, are lacking, as are telecom regulators,” Chalupa added.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of the many points of conflict.
Clearly, there is a relevant market analysis carried out by the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> according to which telecommunications are, from the point of view of commercial tendering, a single market.
In this type of market, of course, none of the Czech operators have a dominant position.
However, some of the legal experts offer another view - for a virtual operator to emerge, agreement with the network administrator is always necessary.
And the mobile operator - with all its logic - has a monopoly on its network.
Therefore, in a particular segment it must necessarily be dominant.
And if this argument is not accepted, at least for <0xC3><0x9A>OHS it should be a warning that three mobile operators rise strikingly similarly.
The current complaints of the interested parties (influenced by the aforementioned company GTS Novera) show that in all negotiations with the operators they are faced with many similar impediments.
Carrying responsibility on the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> is a fairly common trick in the field of telecommunications from which the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS washes its hands in all this matter.
We have met with him already in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, a new amendment to the Telecommunications Act was tabled recently to broaden <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>'s competence in the field of commercial tendering, which was not implemented, even though a number of specialists promised that the situation would improve.
This should be perfectly known to UOHS representatives, but it is clear that their interests lie elsewhere.
It's all right, when no one looks
At the same time, something like a pseudo-virtual operator continues to work unnoticed, since there are already a few in Czech mobile networks.
They are companies that put their own prices on mobile phone services that, however, only a part are public.
These are usually companies that are engaged in multi-level marketing.
Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
Usually only a select few get the price list of these companies.
The magic is that the company, with respect to the carrier, acts as a classic business customer of the same ordering a large number of SIM cards.
As a special customer you will then receive special prices and other offers.
The problem is that commercial conditions at all Czech mobile operators prohibit such resale.
"If cases such as those cited were discovered, it could be a violation of the contract conditions that could result in the end of the collaboration with the given society," Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> answered the question about this problem.
But it is quite unlikely that such an activity carried out by mobile operators would not reach responsible people.
It is precisely in the case of the three companies mentioned that they can reach thousands of customers.
None of the operators are against this procedure.
With the activities of these companies they make a not inconsiderable profit and, at the same time - unlike the real virtual operators - in no way threaten their own official marketing.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> warns us of possible problems: "the law allows such speculation, however, the services of this company are used only by a negligible so much percent of customers.
They must also accept that the SIM card on their phone is not in their name so they cannot absolutely dispose of it as a normal customer of the carriers.
Precisely this is what should seem to the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> at the very least strange.
There is also a new question for the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
If mobile operators are turning their eyes in this type of procedure, why are they blocking the entry of the virtual operator?
It is necessary to add that the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS has enough competence to discover this type of activities and if it is not going to want it should not be content with the explanations of the operators that they have no idea of this history and that their commercial conditions do not allow it.
When will we stop being the most expensive
As was already clear in the text, the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile phone market brought a significant decrease in the prices of the services.
At the same time, in virtually all the countries where the virtual operator emerged, the classic operators more or less tried to protect themselves from this intrusion.
The arguments used by these were virtually all identical - too small, a market eventually too saturated, problems with the quality of service, etc.
In the most advanced countries, however, regulators have now intervened and in none of the cases defended the operators but their customers.
Whether it was with formal measures or informal pressure, the first virtual operator emerged and with it, more began to emerge.
Unfortunately, the Czech Regulatory Authority passes this whole case as if it were a burning nail.
From our experience we cannot fail to be impressed that the confusion of attributions in these cases suits them.
But let us not despair.
If this behind-the-scenes information is correct and the virtual operator actually gets to these lands, then the Czech mobile market is likely to start moving again.
If any of the operators allows a virtual mobile operator to enter, it will be difficult for the UOHS to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of other interested parties.
And we will perhaps stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
