New York City has thousands of avenues, boulevards, streets and other roads, some famous, others simply service.
However, many people, including veteran taxi drivers and longtime local residents, find it difficult to pinpoint the location of Extra Place, especially since many of them have never heard of this street.
The small street is located in the East Village and extends north of First Street – before I found Second Street – between Bowery and Second Avenue.
This little street, roughly 30 feet wide and 120 feet long, resembles a dusty alleyway more than one active track.
There's no sign.
It is practically impossible to find in an atlas.
The street, however, has admirers.
For example, there is Avalon Bay, the company that has recently built luxury buildings on First Street.
who wants to repaint Extra Place and create a clean corridor to the shops and boutiques that are expected to open in the new buildings.
Other admirers include old-time neighbors who commented that they were delighted by the truncated lane simply because it is one of the last remnants of the block’s past before the appropriation of the buildings.
However, the city’s Housing, Preservation and Development Department, which has control of the street, has no interest in owning it.
At this month’s Land Use Community Committee meeting, Avalon agency representatives outlined a proposal to buy the street.
However, the committee, preferring the street to remain in the city, called for a new plan to be presented next month, as Community District Manager Susan Stetzer said.
"The city owns very few spaces today and we would like it to continue to own Extra Place," said Ms.
“We can consider the proposals made by Avalon to solve the problem and manage the space, but we also want to ensure public access to the street.”
Avalon Bay had announced several months ago that it wanted to repair the small street and install some seats, including some to be used as coffee, waiting to rent the spaces.
The idea that Avalon could buy the street first came up during this month’s meeting.
But Michele de Milly, a spokeswoman for Avalon Bay, said that even though the company wanted to use the street, it didn’t necessarily want to own it.
“Avalon Bay’s primary concern is the renovation of this abandoned alley and the possibility of turning it into a public area,” he said, adding that the proposed sale came from the city itself.
Seth Donlin, a spokesman for the Preservation Committee, confirmed that it was the city’s desire to sell the street and noted that the agency’s mission is to develop the property rather than manage it.
Compared to its more colourful surroundings, those of the Bowery, Extra Place has left a mark on history.
Some believe it got its name in 1802, when the large estate owned by Philip Minthorne was divided among his sons and this narrow strip of land was not claimed by anyone.
The back door of the CBGB, the punk rock monument that closed in 2006, opened in Extra Place, but the street is perhaps best known for the establishment's photograph on the cover of Ramones' album "Rocket to Russia".
"The setting was magnificent," said Danny Fields, the Ramones' manager, who took the picture in November 1976.
"It was full of trash, pieces of clothes and pieces of barrels, posters, sheets, ropes."
Some residents, including bloggers who write about the East Village bourgeoisization, have opposed the idea of selling Extra Place, arguing that public goods, even modest ones, must remain public.
Others have praised Extra Place as a rare piece, virtually unchanged, a sliver of the city that should be guarded.
Jeremy Moss, who runs a blog called Jeremiah's Vanishing New York (subtitle, "The Book of Lamentations: A Bitterly Nostalgic Look at a City in the Process of Going Extinct"), has made available part of a talk on the city's history of Extra Place, published by The New Yorker in 1952.
The author, Brendan Gill, wrote: "Extra Place is a somewhat narrow and dead-end alley, dark also by day and marked by rusty iron warehouse doors and shutters, with week-old newspapers blown along the gutters."
With few exceptions, the street looked more or less the same on a recent afternoon.
A rat was cured through the back of the street and stopped near the door that was used to enter the CBGB and now houses a luxury clothing store.
Graffiti on the walls and an empty beer bottle of about 22-oz were near a new batch of discarded newspapers.
Some interns said they rarely paid attention to Extra Place, but suggested it could be cleaned up.
Mr. Fields, for his part, noted that some people underestimate the attractive power of the street in its current state.
"I spent the best years of my life," he said, "in dark, wet, and disgusting places."
