Effectively calling Hispanic voters is a difficult business.
Barack Obama’s education proposals are an example of that.
Mr. Obama’s campaign notes that “African Americans and Latino students are significantly less likely to graduate than white students,” and this is a very certain consideration.
To combat such differences in learning events, Obama’s education plan specifically advocates, among other things, “bilingual transition education” for English-students.
However, the open question for Mr. Obama is whether the commitment of bilingual education, which prefers classroom instruction in languages other than English, is effective in overriding the distance in the final results.
Take, for example, Sixth Street Prep, an officially recognized primary school in the eastern region of Los Angeles County.
In this school the vast majority of students are Hispanic and low-income families:
More than a third of students, many of whom are newcomers, are learning the English language.
However, an incredible 100 percent of fourth-year students have been positively assessed in the 2008 math exam.
and almost an equally astounding 93 percent have mastered the English language and arts test.
This incredible success has been achieved using a different ingredient than Mr. Obama favored.
The Sixth Street School emphasizes review and practice, constant assessment of competencies and does not tolerate any attitude of excuses.
Also, and this is where Mr. Obama should take note, according to Linda Mikels, the principal of Sixth Street, the school’s focus for English instruction to students is on “total immersion.”
Immersion in English means the almost exclusive use of the language in the treatment of the contents of the instruction.
Ms. Mikels, who opposes bilingual education, told me, “We’ve had extraordinary successes with students like this last one coming in from Mexico and that if you walked into the classroom 12 months later you wouldn’t be able to pick up what it was.”
