While it is that immigrants should learn English, recently Mr. Obama has trivialized the issue by letting people stop worrying about legislation that is only written in English.
and instead, he said, "you should make sure your child can speak Spanish."
If Mr. Obama really wants to improve the system and close gaps, he should carefully consider models of education that work well, rather than scorn or trivialize them.
Oil prices fall sharply after renewed economic fears
Oil prices fell sharply on Monday because of concerns that the U.S. bailout for financial markets may not be able to revive the economy.
Crude oil shares fell 7 percent to $99.80 a barrel in early morning trading on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
The price has fallen by more than $20 per barrel since last Monday.
In the past two weeks, commodity markets have been rocked by the Wall Street financial crisis and a couple of powerful hurricanes in the Gulf of Mexico.
After hitting a high of $145.29 per barrel in July, prices had fallen to nearly $90 per barrel earlier this month, before retreating once again due to huge uncertainty in financial markets.
Anxiety gripped investors once again on Monday, despite congressional leaders saying they had reached an agreement over the weekend on the bailout plan, the largest in history.
The news was overshadowed by new concerns that the financial crisis would be far from over.
The evolution that occurred in the latest episode of the merger process confirms that Citigroup will buy the banking operations of Wachovia Corporation, according to what the government said on Monday.
Meanwhile, the Belgian, Dutch and Luxembourg governments have partially nationalized the European financial conglomerate Fortis.
Analysts at Barclays Capital said that, over the frantic weekend, the negotiations that led to the bailout “seem to have failed to rekindle market sentiment.”
As the economic situation deteriorates, demand for commodities, including oil, is expected to fall.
“The outlook for global equity, interest rate and exchange rate will become increasingly uncertain,” Deutsche Bank analysts wrote in a note to investors.
“We believe that commodities will not be able to escape this contagion.
From a product perspective, our most pressing concern is the assessment of whether the American virus will spread globally and specifically to China.”
