These people portrayed "on the street" are artists capable of transmitting on stage passion, sadness, joy... captivating the public.
To capture the personality of these artists you do not have to take pictures of the stage.
They carry their personality and character within.
What interested me was to create an intimate atmosphere that allowed me to capture with the camera the personality of the greats of flamenco."
With the taste of the "Singing of the Mines" festival, Bauer began in 1997 a long journey to portray singers, guitarists or dancers with a plate camera.
These are portraits that, due to the selection of the camera and the material, recall classical photography.
The application of different stylistic means breaks with the classical basis of the image, giving it modernity, an idea that reflects how Bauer himself understands flamenco: "A music with very traditional roots, which evolves and surprises every day".
It is not the action of the dance, the singing or the touch itself, but the personality of the artist, his character, that captivates the public with his art.
The search for an encounter with the essential, with the elf that becomes visible in a way of feeling, being and being are and have been the constant of this work that is presented these days in the gallery El Fot<0xC3><0xB3>mata.
Known flamenco figures such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others, make up this selection of almost seventy photographed artists.
The project has become an anthology of flamenco, which will soon be published in a book that will collect the portraits exhibited in the exhibition.
Bauer's passion for portraits led him to repeat the idea two years ago with "Portraits of Veteran Athletes" ("SportARTproject").
Although the concepts are different in "Flamenco-people", the photographer admits that "I love to portray people, meet them and be able to enter a moment in their life, be it a long or short moment.
I think that within photography, portraiture is the most difficult genre.
You meet or confront people, characters, who sometimes you don’t even know, or who only give you a few minutes to take the photo.
In spite of these circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to make my ideas come true.”
This collection of portraits of current flamenco under the title "Flamenco-people" is on display at the Galer<0xC3><0xAD>a El Fot<0xC3><0xB3>mata, located at number 20 of Calle de la Mata, parallel to the Alameda de Hércules, where it can be visited until October 16.
