Speaking in Sleep
Some children talk at night.
I am not referring to those who wake up very smart telling us something that happened the day before, but to children who talk while they are asleep.
The first time it happens, you may get scared, but it doesn’t really matter.
It is a benign sleep disorder called somniloquia.
It is quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
I'm sure more than one has been told that he spoke at night.
This phenomenon can occur very sporadically (once in life for example associated with an episode of high fever), or more periodically (every day, once a week, once in a month), the next day the child does not remember anything.
There is no single cause that determines its appearance.
They are often related to other sleep disturbances such as nightmares, night terrors, bedwetting (sleeping) or sleepwalking, but it doesn’t have to be.
As we have already mentioned above, they can also be associated with very high fever, stress or overexcitation situations.
It is an understudied phenomenon anyway.
The intensity with which it appears is also very variable.
He may speak in a calm tone of voice, loose words, a murmur or the opposite (crying, crying, long speeches...).
In cases where the manifestation is very intense it is advisable to observe the child and consult with a specialist, to check if there is any issue that is generating a lot of anxiety and gives it out in this way.
We have said that it is a benign disorder, so it has no treatment, unless it is associated with another sleep disorder that can be treated (for example, if it is associated with sleep apnea or a stress picture).
What can be done is to take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child too much before going to sleep.
Therefore look for quiet games and avoid programs or TV series that are scary or a little violent.
With children who are very nervous and find it difficult to relax, relaxation techniques can be used to help them acquire a certain inner calm.
This will help the child to have a calmer sleep.
Once the somniloquies appear try to stay calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will remember nothing of what has happened.
Useful Tips
Don't wake him.
It is useless, because he is not conscious, and you will break his sleep.
Even though he’s talking, he’s sleeping and therefore resting.
Remember that if you are very distressed during several episodes you should consult or find out what is causing so much anxiety in the child.
If you understand what he says (which is not the most common), do not fall into the temptation to interrogate him for information.
You will achieve nothing, because being asleep is not conscious enough to organize his thought.
Also you will hear what he says, but you do not know what he is dreaming to say that, so be very careful in how you interpret the information and with the conclusions you draw.
Never tell the child that you can interrogate him at night to find out his secrets.
Not even a joke.
That creates a lot of anxiety.
In short, do not worry, it is not bad, it is an episode that lasts only a few minutes.
