Psychology of Overlaps: Why Do We Spend More Money?
Auction participants are likely to spend more money and overvalue the product.
Neurologists and economists at New York University discovered the neurological-economic basis of this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to the study published in the journal Science, people do not want to lose in competitions such as eBay auctions, so they prefer to pay even an excessive price.
The scientists tried to establish the neurological scheme of this "game" through experimental auctions.
One of the groups of volunteers played the lottery, the other participated in an auction and in the meantime the active brain areas of the people participating in the experiment were examined using the functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) system.
In both games participants could earn money, but during the auctions, where it is fundamental to bet more than the other, losing the game intensified the operation of the complex called stratum located under the cerebral cortex.
This area of the brain, in addition to many other functions, plays a role in the “self-reward” mechanism of the nervous system.
Thus, according to the scientists, the increase in bets is explained as a prevention so as not to provoke an intense reaction of the stratum.
To substantiate their theory, the economists of the scientific group also conducted a financial follow-up study.
In this experiment three groups bet against one person under different circumstances.
The control group was simply told the real value of the product in question, and its members bet.
Another group was also promised that if they won, they would receive an additional $15 in prize money.
Instead, the third group received exactly $15 before the auction, but in case of losing the auction the members of the group lost even that money.
Thus the only difference between the two groups was that for one the triumph was highlighted and for the other the failure.
However, by testing the neurologists’ hypothesis, the members of the group who played “against failure” were willing to bet even more than the members of the control group and the “winner” group.
“These results cannot be deduced from any previously existing economic theory.
For up to now they explained the phenomena of auctions only with the joy of winning and with the prevention of risks.
Only visual neurological methods helped to resolve this contradiction between the two theories, so we now come to a third explanation," said Andrew Schotter, a professor in the faculty of economics at New York University.
Hepatitis: When should you go to the doctor?
Around 500 million people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary chronic liver disease is considered one of the leading causes of death.
The number of people infected in this country is estimated at 100,000, but only 7,000 receive treatment because many of the sick do not know that they are infected.
The name hepatitis is the common name for different liver diseases caused by viruses.
The symptoms are very similar; liver infection and jaundice are characteristic, but their pathogens and the diseases caused are very different.
Hepatitis viruses in dependence on the pathogen are spread by two main forms: hepatitis A and E by food (e.g. with water or contaminated food), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and body humours (sperm, vagina humour, saliva).
Travelers are advised to protect themselves by vaccine against the A and B virus, against C there are no vaccines.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after consuming the infected food, manifested by a poor general condition, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After that appear on the skin and on the white of the eyes jaundice, the excrement becomes clear, the urine dark in color and the healing can last even two - three weeks.
Every year one million people die worldwide from cancer and liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B, the most severe forms of this disease.
The main reason for this is that, according to calculations, only one in ten infected people receives pharmacological treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: without treatment it can produce liver cirrhosis and even cancer.
Most infected people do not know that they are sick because this pathological agent gradually destroys liver cells and often the first symptoms only appear 20-30 years later.
Therefore, it is very important to have premature recognition, systematic medical check-up.
It is much more common in three groups: people who had a blood transfusion before 1991, drug users, and those who wear tattoos.
There are currently about 200 million people in the world who suffer from chronic hepatitis C.
As this disease can be discovered with a routine laboratory control as well, it is worth consulting with the family doctor when experiencing any unknown symptoms.
The disease has a cure if it is discovered in time, it is possible to exterminate the virus from the body, so it can suppress the contagion and prevent cancer.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, which was first organized in 2004 by organizations representing the sick.
Its goal is to draw attention to the causes of chronic liver infections caused by viruses and the importance of their premature recognition.
