Industrial prices continue to rise
In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 percent compared to last month's prices and by 12.9 percent compared to prices in August 2007 - the Central Bureau of Statistics (KSH) reported.
Industrial export prices rose 1.1 percent from July 2008 and decreased 3.9 percent from the previous year.
And as a result of changes in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 percent over the previous month and by 3.2 percent over the previous year.
Industrial sales prices rose only to a minimal extent, by 0.1 percent.
Domestic sales prices of processing industry sectors rose minimally, at 0.1 percent from July.
The largest increase in price magnitude occurred in August 2008 in the leather and footwear production sector (2.8 percent), primarily due to a 4.6 percent monthly increase in bags and belts and a 2.5 percent increase in footwear.
The higher price level of plastic and chemical base materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in the prices of the chemical production branch (1.6 percent).
There was a decrease in price in the petrochemical sector, (1.4 percent), in the production of electrical machines and instruments (0.9 percent), as well as - to a minimum extent - in the wood processing sectors (0.1 percent).
The prices of papermaking, publishing and printing did not change.
In the rest of the sectors of the processing industry, there was a price increase of between 0.2 and 0.9 percent.
In the supply of electricity, gas, heat and water, which represent a major weight in domestic trade, an increase of 0.3 percent was recorded in August, first as a result of the effect of the increase in official prices as of July 1.
In a twelve-month period comparison - in domestic sales of processing industry sectors - the largest price increase was recorded in the petrochemical sector (32.4 percent).
In the metal processing sector, an increase of 13.2 percent was observed, while in the food, beverage and tobacco industry, of determining weight, there was an increase of 11 percent.
There was a decrease in prices in the textile industry (2.5 percent), as well as in the manufacture of electrical machines and instruments (0.3 percent).
In the rest of the processing sectors, the pace of price growth was between 0.6 and 9.1 percent.
During the past year in the processing industry globally, prices increased by 10.2 percent.
Electricity, gas, heat and water prices exceeded previous year’s prices by 18.7 percent.
In August, among the different sectors of domestic trade, the largest monthly price increase (0.7 percent) was recorded in the investment goods sectors.
In the consumer goods sectors, prices increased by 0.3 percent, in the energy sector and the intermediate sectors there was no change compared to the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month of the previous year, the largest price increase occurred in the energy sectors and in the intermediary industry (16.8 percent).
In the branches that produce consumer goods, there was a decrease of 6.8 percent and in investment goods of 1.4 percent.
Industry export prices calculated in HUF increased by 1.1 percent over the previous month, and compared to 12 months, there was a decrease of 3.9 percent.
