Brussels had asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, seeing the large use of portable musical devices and the increase in the number of young people exposed to the noise that causes it.
"Scientists confirm that this is a matter of concern and the European Commission will now examine together with Member States and stakeholders what measures could eventually be taken to better protect children and adolescents from exposure to noise from portable musical devices and related devices."
Currently, there is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable musical devices to 100 dB, but concern increases as hearing damage that can result from excessive exposure to such noise sources.
It is possible to greatly limit these damages by resorting to solutions such as reducing levels and time of exposure to noise.
In its opinion, the EU Scientific Committee points out that if users of portable musical devices listen to music at high volume (more than 89 decibels) for only 5 hours a week, they exceed the current limit for maximum noise allowed in the workplace.
