Both in the United States and in Europe for a long time the crisis seems to work as an accelerator of incubation phenomena that with the new climate solidify and come to light.
The first of these phenomena is the re-updating, the extraordinary reactivation, of the double category state-sovereignty in relation to a type of renationalization of the economy.
The crisis, indeed, is a crisis of banking-financial institutions which have, yes, strong financial relations with the outside, but above all the balance sheets of families living in a single country and in a single state are much more compromised.
The one that immediately creates a political problem for those who govern it: that is, how to respond to the difficulty and protests of those people and those families who, on the other hand, are voters.
The crisis appears economically global but is politically and exclusively national.
Political internationalism seems substantially out of the question or they don’t have much to say: the crucial test is the European Union which, as always, divides between the different interests and the different state strategies and fails to decide any common policy.
