Farewell to the old cinema Paradiso, the cities cancel the historic rooms
Historical cinemas close favoring Multiplexes.
“A city without movie theaters in a blind city, it’s like a face without eyes.”
The image offered by director Giuseppe Tornatore effectively photographs what is happening in large Italian urban centers and also in provincial cities.
The process of marginalization of cinemas, which with the birth of the great meticones in the periphery and the consequent disappearance of the mono halls in the central areas of the city, is an inevitable and indisputable event with all the characteristics of a true cultural crime.
To disappear almost always are historical places, full of memory, "it is as if a friend died, an acquaintance with whom a piece of place and so much emotion was shared", Observes the director of the new cinema Paradiso, the film that twenty years ago won the cousin Oscar and the grand prize of the jury at Cannes, which told the poetry of a provincial cinema and the nostalgia for the way of living the cinema that ever lost.
The figures given by the Anec, the main association of merchants, speak clearly: in the last five years they have closed 316 traditional cinemas, and to pay for most are mainly the halls of the main cities: 10 less in Florence, 9 less in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closures are first, Emilia-Romagna with 82 fewer cinemas, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
It is a demonstration that the person responsible for its disappearance is the arrival of the multiplex, these are the three Italian regions that have recorded the largest number of new meticulous cinemas: 195 more screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in Tuscany than in Emilia-Romagna.
“The Italian exercise has developed irrationally,” observes Paolo Protti, president of Anec, “it would be useful to build new structures but it would be necessary to ensure the permanence of those already existing, because when a city hall closes, not all its frequenters are willing to transfer to the meticons.
Not to mention the lack of funds in favor of traders: the previous debt of the state is about 10 million euros.
It is ethically and morally shameful that the government does not respect the laws that exist.
To sustain the sector would serve between 16 and 18 million euros per year.
Interestingly the case of Bologna, the first Italian city that worried about the closures, decided to repair itself with the signing of a protocol between the municipality and Anec, the first of its kind in Italy to promote and protect the cinema mono sala both in the historic center and in the periphery.
Among the rules envisaged are mediated tax facilitation in favour of managers and advantages for the public in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the restricted traffic area and will have special rates for parking.
“It’s an initiative that I like,” Giuseppe Tornatore observes, “and I hope that other cities will follow Bologna’s example by setting up other measures.
It is true, that to contrast the extra power of meticons, traditional rooms have to improve the quality of sound and image because the public today is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a subject that was always important to me: the closure of the Bagheria cinema, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to make the "New Cinema Paradiso", which I had been thinking for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass the Rialto or the Quirinale of Via Nazionale already closed, where I have lived so many shared emotions, so as not to see the posters blackened by the dust, I turn to the other side.
