When the energy is born from the waves, the big ones come down to the stage.
It is an exterminated deposit that occupies more than 70% of the planet’s surface and is now being discovered by the world’s largest energy companies.
Waves, currents, tides are the new renewable sources on which the great ones like Chevron look.
The possibility of collecting energy from the movements of the sea has been studied for a hundred years and in the 1970s together with the first oil crisis, investigations intensified.
When the price of oil went down in 1980, the idea of harnessing marine energy was put aside, but now that environmental cases and the new increase in oil give impetus to the sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London has estimated by 2007 that 15 percent of the world’s electricity need could be covered by implants that exploit the movement of sea waves.
This would be twice the amount currently produced by nuclear power plants.
And then there would be the currents and the tides.
Giants to attack.
The first company to bet on marine energy has been Enersis, which in 2005 has sealed an agreement to build an implant in the North of Portugal.
When the intention was announced it seemed like a revolutionary step.
Two years away to bet on marine energy are always more and among these companies that have always voted for traditional energy.
“Chevron is studying ocean energy technology,” a spokesman for a company associated with the U.S. oil giant told the Wall Street Journal, “and is evaluating the possibility of cooperating with us.”
The cooperation in question is about obtaining a permit from the U.S. Energy Commission, to carry out a project to exploit marine energy in Alaska.
It’s a pretty important sign, considering that in Alaska the U.S. continues to mine oil and recently President Bush has activated a plan to conduct new drilling.
In addition to Chevron is Verdant Power Inc. of New York and Ocean Power of New Jersey to follow the path of energy coming from the sea, the total invested so far, although they are not detailed indicate an increasing interest.
Technology to develop.
Experts are talking about a technology still in its infancy, because marine energy has no doubts that it has a great environmental impact.
For now, impacts like those of the Portuguese or the Scots are small and do not seem to create major problems for the ecosystem.
To produce energy on a large scale, a technology with a greater environmental impact must be used.
And the options are several: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of boas joined together.
The force of the waves, which causes the boas to move up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure with pistons and cylinders inside them.
The pressure rotates a turbine which in turn feeds a generator.
Electricity is sent to the coast via submarine cables.
For now there are four implants of this type in development, waiting only for federal approval, apart from energy, could serve for a military installation.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, is already producing power for a shopping mall and a parking lot, using underwater turbines on New York’s East River.
The movement of water when there are tides, rotates the turbine blades, creating a rotating motion that feeds the generator.
Verdant has said it has a long list of customers waiting for the necessary authorizations to use the energy.
After the waves, the tides.
A particular interest, they say at the Institute for the Development of Electricity, deserves right now the potential of the tides.
Although it is an intermittent phenomenon, tides are more preventable than wind, sun or waves and therefore more reliable as a source of energy.
It is mainly about tidal energy that states such as New York, Maine and Alaska, together with others approaching the coasts, have invested $7.5 million in 2008 and an investment of $35 million is planned for 2009.
